<title>UK: UK BRC April retail sales survey - table.</title>
<headline>UK BRC April retail sales survey - table.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1996-05-13</dateline>
<text>
<p>The British Retail Consortium published the following data on UK retail sales value in April (annual percentage changes):</p>
<p>		  TOTAL	 LIKE-FOR-LIKE</p>
<p> April	    7.4	    4.1</p>
<p> March	    7.1	    3.7</p>
<p> February	 7.9	    4.3</p>
<p> January	  8.5	    4.9</p>
<p> December 1996  7.8	    4.5</p>
<p> November	 8.0	    4.9</p>
<p> October	  9.4	    5.9</p>
<p> September	8.7	    5.2</p>
<p> August	  10.7	    6.9</p>
<p> July	     8.9	    5.4</p>
<p> June	    10.6	    7.0</p>
<p> May	     10.3	    6.2</p>
<p> April	    3.8	    0.4</p>
<p> March	   12.2	    7.5</p>
<p> Feb		6.9	    3.6</p>
<p> Jan 1996	 7.8	    4.1</p>
<p> Dec  1995	7.3	    4.3</p>
<p> Nov		6.7	    3.2</p>
<p> Oct		5.7	    2.4</p>
<p> Sept	     6.8	    3.4</p>
<p> Aug		5.3	    2.0</p>
<p> July	     7.3	    3.4</p>
<p> June	     6.4	    3.0</p>
<p> May		7.5	    3.9</p>
<p> April	    9.9	    5.9</p>
<p> March	    2.1	   -1.2</p>
<p> Feb		7.5	    3.3</p>
<p> Jan 1995	 2.5	   -1.0</p>
<p>NOTE - The retail sales monitor measures changes in actual value of retail sales from a sample of 75 retailers who account for around half total UK retail sales. Figures are re-weighted to remove any bias in the sample towards specific categories of spending. They are not otherwise adjusted for change in seasonal influences (such as the timing of Easter) or price changes.</p>
<p>The BRC says like-for-like figures in general provide a more accurate guide to spending patterns, removing the effect of any expansion in retail floor space on sales.</p>
<p>The latest survey covers the four weeks to May 3.</p>
